<div id="review_4047595445" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4047595445" />
    <a title="Trish" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3461034-trish"><img alt="Trish" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1588663568p2/3461034.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4047595445?book_show_action=true">Jun 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Trish" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Trish" href="/user/show/3461034-trish">Trish</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audiobook 9783981653960" href="/book/show/53402459-auf-silberner-f-hrte">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4047595445" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7878726275773370961">It might seem weird to some, but I love the hardcover version of these books while also being in love with the audio editions. Which is why I read the book twice, kinda. <br/><br/>As already detailed in <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3378878284' rel='nofollow noopener'>my review of the hardcover edition</a>, this 4th volume takes us to Mirrorworld‘s version of Japan where we visit the island of foxes and therefore more shapeshifters like Celeste (in a way). <br/>Jacob and Fuchs are trying to find a way not to have to give their firstborn to Spieler. So they are trying to find oth</span>
  <span id="freeText7878726275773370961" style="display:none">It might seem weird to some, but I love the hardcover version of these books while also being in love with the audio editions. Which is why I read the book twice, kinda. <br><br>As already detailed in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3378878284" rel="nofollow noopener">my review of the hardcover edition</a>, this 4th volume takes us to Mirrorworld‘s version of Japan where we visit the island of foxes and therefore more shapeshifters like Celeste (in a way). <br>Jacob and Fuchs are trying to find a way not to have to give their firstborn to Spieler. So they are trying to find other Earl elves and a way to either trick or defeat Spieler, who has brought Clara to Mirrorworld.<br>Will is trying to find Spieler together with Nerron to avenge having been played for a fool. But then he learns some details about his father (while we readers learn even more about Will‘s parentage).<br>Meanwhile, fae magic is alive and … well, not kicking, it‘s too weak for that. But a certain dead coachman teams up with a Japanese tour guide and takes Fuchs to another Earl elf who indeed offers help.<br>Will fae magic survive / the fae come back? Can Jacob and Celeste save their unborn child? Can Jacob survive teaming up with Nerron?<br>I can tell you that the ending was quite a torturous cliffhanger that has me crave and lust after the final volume already. :D<br><br>Samurai, a centaur, a nine-tailed fox, ghosts, a child-eating witch, shapeshifters and even some old friends all populate this colourful installment of the series. But we’re not just staying in Japan - we’re also travelling to Mirrorworld’s version of Persia. A colourful background with delicious environments.<br><br>The music of this audio production matches the wonderful and (to me) exotic places the characters are visiting. The quality of the audiobooks is seriously impressive. Not to mention that I have found out what the CD boxes look like. So pretty!<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1623333914i/31470602._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1623333914i/31470603._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1623333914i/31470604._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>So no, I don‘t regret having read the book twice as both reading experiences had its own and unique style / advantages.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7878726275773370961" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


