<div id="review_3378878284" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3378878284" />
    <a title="Trish" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3461034-trish"><img alt="Trish" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1588663568p2/3461034.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3378878284?book_show_action=true">Jun 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Trish" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Trish" href="/user/show/3461034-trish">Trish</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3378878284" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6781630302046153586">The 4th volume in my favorite series by this greatest of contemporary German author (if you as me).<br/><br/>Jacob and Fuchs have travelled to Mirrorworld‘s version of Japan. The island of foxes is especially interesting to Celeste, of course, but they meet up and then travel with Nerron and Will. <br/>Spieler‘s plan has layer upon layer and he suddenly appears with Clara in tow.<br/>Will wants revenge for having been played while also looking for a cure for 16, but Jacob and Celeste/Fuchs simply want to save their</span>
  <span id="freeText6781630302046153586" style="display:none">The 4th volume in my favorite series by this greatest of contemporary German author (if you as me).<br><br>Jacob and Fuchs have travelled to Mirrorworld‘s version of Japan. The island of foxes is especially interesting to Celeste, of course, but they meet up and then travel with Nerron and Will. <br>Spieler‘s plan has layer upon layer and he suddenly appears with Clara in tow.<br>Will wants revenge for having been played while also looking for a cure for 16, but Jacob and Celeste/Fuchs simply want to save their unborn child from the deal with the Earl elf.<br>And all that while there seems to be some fae magic left! Weak, but definitely still there. But will it survive / be enough considering the formidable foe Spieler has invited to Mirrorworld?<br>Thus begins a quest for what the Dark One has done to give our favorite treasure hunter duo a fighting chance. Though they don‘t know that is actually what they are searching for as they are currently too occupied with re-finding each other and staying alive.<br>Moreover, we learn much more about the pst of the Reckless family - which also shows the long game Spieler is playing. And we meet other elves (and my, are they all different)!<br><br>What a ride! A relatively „slow“ (not boring, just not action-laden) beginning is the prelude to one hell of a journey through a new and fascinating corner of Mirrorworld (that also includes Parsien which is Mirrorworld‘s version of Persia) that not only features Jacob and Nerron teaming up but also has us meet samurai, a centaur, a nine-tailed fox, ghosts, a child-eating witch, shapeshifters and even some old friends. <br><br>The ending is a bit mean. *lol* It is quite the cliffhanger, you see. I know there will be only one more book now and I can hardly wait to finally have it in my greedy little bookwormish fingers. :D<br><br>And, of course, we get many more gorgeous illustrations by the author. Once again, the publisher has decided to only use small illustrations at the beginning of the chapters instead of also adorning the text itself but alas. See below a few examples to know why I‘m so in love with the author‘s art:<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1623689174i/31490092._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1623689174i/31490093._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1623689174i/31490094._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1623689174i/31490095._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1623689174i/31490096._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1623689174i/31490097._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>I can‘t stop caressing my hardcover though I also read this book in its audio format (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4047595445" rel="nofollow noopener">see my review here</a>).<br><br>So no, I don‘t regret having read the book twice as both reading experiences had its own and unique style / advantages.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6781630302046153586" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


