<div id="review_3625048110" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3625048110" />
    <a title="Cocoanatomical" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/113300833-cocoanatomical"><img alt="Cocoanatomical" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1596296515p2/113300833.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3625048110?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cocoanatomical" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cocoanatomical" href="/user/show/113300833-cocoanatomical">Cocoanatomical</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3625048110&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3625048110" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6101514898452595503">I did enjoy the storyline over all, it‘s definitely a book that adds to the series.<br/>I really love how ambivalent and flawed most of the characters are, which in my opinion makes them much more relatable and interesting.<br/>I’m also thankful for the little queer representation we got with Hideo but I’m still waiting for Will and Nerron to fall in love passionately. Seriously, they were missing each other/ thinking about each other throughout the whole book...<br/><br/>There are still a couple of things that I h</span>
  <span id="freeText6101514898452595503" style="display:none">I did enjoy the storyline over all, it‘s definitely a book that adds to the series.<br />I really love how ambivalent and flawed most of the characters are, which in my opinion makes them much more relatable and interesting.<br />I’m also thankful for the little queer representation we got with Hideo but I’m still waiting for Will and Nerron to fall in love passionately. Seriously, they were missing each other/ thinking about each other throughout the whole book...<br /><br />There are still a couple of things that I have my problems with:<br />Writing from a white western perspective about other cultures is always tricky and can quickly turn into cultural appropriation. That applies to our real world as much as it does to a mirror world in which myths and fairy tales come to life.<br />I felt like the Japanese setting in the book overall was treated respectfully. This is especially portrayed through the character Fuchs who is really considerate in her relationship with Hideo and his culture. At the same time the narrative still puts Hideo in a position in which he is serving Fuchs as a protector - at times rather submissively - and I really felt like he did deserve more agency in the book.<br />Some of the parts involving Hideos magical Irezumi felt somewhat cringeworthy though I do not know enough about traditional Japanese tattooing and Japanese myths to really speak on this.<br />Another thing that I was very surprised by is the use of an absolutely outdated German word to describe Native Americans. One would assume that at least one of the editors or the publisher would recognize such things and change them.<br /><br />If the next book is really set in a mirror equivalent of North America I really hope that Cornelia Funke does her research properly and maybe consults people from the different communities she wants to reference in the book. Contact them, get their consent, pay them, give credit to them.<br />Disney did it with Frozen II and they did a decent job portraying the Sámi people in Scandinavia.<br />It’s possible to respectfully portray indigenous peoples and their stories, we just got to put in the work.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6101514898452595503" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


